Postharvest Biology and Technology

Apple stem/calyx real-time recognition using YOLO-v5 algorithm for fruit automatic loading system

Author links open overlay panel, , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.postharvbio.2021.111808Get rights and content

Highlights

  • •

    Stem/calyx position play a key role in recognizing fruit posture.

  • •

    Images acquisition system based on fruit posture adjustment equipment was built.

  • •

    The optimized YOLO-v5 algorithm was proposed to recognize apple stem/calyx.

  • •

    The algorithm could realize real-time detection under CPU condition.

Abstract

Fruit loading and packaging are still labor-intensive tasks during postharvest commercialization, of which the key issues is to realize the real-time detection and adjustment of fruit posture. However, fruit stem/calyx position is a key structural characteristic for fruit posture and will also affect fruit internal quality detection. In this paper, an image acquisition system based on fruit posture adjustment equipment was set up, and the YOLO-v5 algorithm based on deep learning was used to study the real-time recognition of stem/calyx of apples. First, hyperparameters were determined, and the training method of transfer learning was used to obtain better detection performance; then the networks with different widths and depths were trained to find the best baseline detection net; finally, the YOLO-v5 algorithm was optimized for this task by using detection head searching, layer pruning and channel pruning. The results showed that under the same setting conditions, YOLO-v5s had a more superior usability and could be selected as the baseline network considering detection performance, model weight size, and detection speed. After optimization, the complexity of the algorithm was further reduced. The model parameters and weight volume were decreased by about 71 %, while mean Average Precision (mAP) and F1-score (F1) were only decreased by 1.57 % and 2.52 %, respectively. The optimized algorithm could achieve real-time detection under CPU condition at a speed of 25.51 frames per second (FPS). In comparison with other deep learning target detection algorithms, the algorithm used in this paper was similar to other lightweight networks in complexity. Its mAP and F1 were 0.880 and 0.851, respectively. This was better than other one-stage object detection algorithms in detection ability, only lower than that of Faster R-CNN. The optimized YOLO-v5s achieved 93.89 % accuracy in fruit stem/calyx detection for different cultivars of apples. This research could lay the foundation for the automation of fruit loading and packing systems.

1. Introduction

In China, the fruit industry has become the third-largest agricultural cultivation industry after food crops and vegetables (Yuan and Chen, 2019). Postharvest commercialization of fruit could reduce the post-harvest loss, intensify their commercial character, and finally increase consumers' desire to buy (Uribe et al., 2020). However, manual work with high cost and low efficiency is still widely used in current commercial post-harvest fruit processing technology, especially in the loading and packing process (Cao et al., 2020). The key to solve this problem is to realize the real-time recognition and adjustment of fruit posture. Considering the structural characteristics of fruit, the detection of fruit stem/calyx position is a prerequisite for fruit posture recognition.

In recent years, there has been a lot of research on non-destructive detection for fruit quality evaluation and disease discrimination (Lu et al., 2020). Some commercial packaging devices with fruit orientation function have also been developed, such as Greefa’s SmartPackr robot, RoboticsPlus’ Aporo apple packer. These studies show that the identification of stem/calyx is not only related to the identification and adjustment of fruit posture, but also affects the accuracy of non-destructive detection of fruit quality and the identification of defects (Baneh et al., 2018; Xu et al., 2019). Therefore, the rapid and accurate identification of fruit stem/calyx will be important to the post-harvest commercialization of fruit in loading, detection, and packaging.

Researchers have done a lot of work on stem/calyx detection (Zhang et al., 2018). For most fruit, the light intensity in the stem/calyx region is relatively low compared to other surfaces. Based on this visual feature, investigators have conducted a number of related studies using traditional machine vision techniques. Some scholars identified the stem/calyx respectively based on the color characteristics (Moallem et al., 2017). In this study, Mahalanobis distance of stem end pixels were used to determine the stem. For calyx, they determined the segmentation threshold through k-means clustering based on Cb component in YCbCr color space. Finally, the average accuracy of stem/calyx was more than 91 %. Zou et al. (2010) used three cameras to collect the surface color features of a single fruit, and extracted region of interest (ROI) by setting threshold segmentation, and counted the number to realize defective fruit identification. The result showed that this design could reduce the classification errors from 15 to 11 % compared with a single camera. Unay and Gosselin (2007) extracted the object shape and texture feature values by threshold segmentation technique and these features were introduced to several supervised classification algorithms. After testing, support-vector machine (SVM) was found to be the best among all algorithms.

The area of fruit stem and calyx is concave, which is obviously different from other surfaces. This special structure also provides another research direction for researchers to study. As early as the last century, some scholars used structured light technology and back-propagation neural networks to identify stems and calyxes, and the average recognition accuracy was 95 % (Yang, 1996). Cubero et al. (2014) analyzed the change in the direction of the curvature of the radius function. For regular fruit, these changes were supposed to be very smooth except unless there was a pedicel/peduncle. Zhang et al. (2015) developed a new computer vision system that uses coded spot-array structured light to identify fruit stem/calyx. The spot-array encoded pattern changes based on concaves were used to locate fruit stem and calyx. They subsequently developed a vision system with near-infrared coded structured light to detect apples with defects in the grading line. The average overall recognition accuracy of the online experiment for three apple cultivars was 90.2 % (Zhang et al., 2017).

The detection accuracy of these traditional target recognition methods is highly dependent on the extracted features and trained classifiers. Some methods require complex and sophisticated acquisition systems, and some may not be available for online applications. In recent years, with the improvement of computer performance, a large number of fruit detection algorithms based on deep learning have been proposed, and their detection performance and speed have been significantly improved (Kamilaris and Prenafeta-Boldú, 2018; Koirala et al., 2019a). Detection algorithms based on deep learning were widely used in agricultural product harvesting (Birrell et al., 2020), disease detection (Barman et al., 2020), yield estimation (Tian et al., 2019), target recognition and tracking (Santos et al., 2020), appearance measurement (Lu and Liaw, 2020). Fan et al. (2020) built a computer vision module to detect apple defects on a commercial packing. The detection performance of the convolutional neural network (CNN) model and that of the SVM classifier were compared. The results showed that the CNN model had a better performance, and it could finish detecting six images of an apple below 72 ms with an accuracy of 92 %. Wu et al. (2020) proposed an automatic detection method for apple defects based on laser-induced light backscattering imaging and CNN algorithm. They established and trained an AlexNet model with an 11-layer structure. The recognition rate of 92.5 % could be obtained, finally. da Costa et al. (2020) proposed a deep neural network binary classifier for detecting external defects in tomatoes. The obtained best model was not confused by the stem/calyx when detecting external defects, and its recall and precision was 86.6 % and 91.7 %, respectively. Zhang et al. (2020) used fully convolutional networks (FCNs) for segmentation blueberries’ internal bruising accurately, the results demonstrated that FCN models have superior performance in calyx segmentation, early bruise detection, and bruise ratio quantification compared with prior SVMs studies.

However, the complex network with higher computing requirements also limits its application. In order to solve this problem, some scholars have carried out efforts on model compression and slimming (Koirala et al., 2019b; Shi et al., 2020). These methods could achieve a balance between detection efficiency and accuracy.

In this paper, in order to solve the needs of real-time posture recognition adjustment for fruit automatic loading system, the research on apples stem/calyx based on YOLO-v5 algorithm was carried out, the specific contents are as follows: (1) using genetic algorithm to optimize the YOLO-v5 hyperparameters; (2) determining and optimizing the best baseline network suitable for fruit stem/calyx; (3) comparing the detection performance of different algorithms, and verifying the generalizability of the algorithms to various types of targets.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Samples used in the experiments

In this research, 325 apple samples were purchased in Gouzhuang fruit wholesale market, Hangzhou, China. As shown in Fig. 1A, apple samples from different production areas include Luochuan Fuji (175), Shanxi Gala (30), Ruixue (30), Ruiyang (30), Shandong Fuji (30) and Zhidan Fuji (30). Among them, 145 Luochuan Fuji apples with different appearances were used for model training, validation and testing. Others were used for model detection to verify the generalization performance of the model. All apples were stored in a cold storage at -2∼0 °C and relative humidity of 85 %. The samples would be kept at room temperature (24−26 °C) for 24 h before the experiment.

2.2. Images acquisition system and dataset creation

2.2.1. Images acquisition system

Images acquisition system was composed of computer, LED lights (Greethink, CX-SMD5630, China), camera (Imaging Source, DFK23G618, Germany) and fruit posture adjustment equipment, as shown in Fig. 1B. Various apple postures were adjusted by the fruit posture adjustment equipment. Then images were taken by the camera, and stored by the computer.

The fruit posture adjustment equipment mainly included drive motors, four Mecanum wheels fitted with rubber flexible rollers (two left-handed wheels and two right-handed wheels), timing belts and the base mounting bracket. The installation method of the Mecanum wheels in a clockwise direction from left to right was right-handed wheel, left-handed wheel, right-handed wheel and left-handed wheel. Two adjacently installed wheels were mirror-symmetrical. Four motors installed under the base mounting bracket driven the corresponding Mecanum wheel through a timing belt. The posture of fruit could be changed by controlling the direction or speed of motors.

2.2.2. Image acquisition and dataset creation

The initial posture of apple was prescribed with the stem area facing directly upwards. Apple centroid was used as the origin of the coordinate system, and the stem-calyx axis was used as the Z-axis. According to the principle of Cartesian coordinate system, two orthogonal horizontal axes were randomly selected as the X-axis and Y-axis. Different apple postures would be captured by the images acquisition system: rotate the apple around its X-axis and Y-axis, respectively, and capture images at an interval of about 30 °. When the stem or calyx area was facing directly upwards, only one photo was taken, respectively. After completing two cycles of rotation, four pictures with the stem facing 45 °, 135 °, 225 ° and 315 ° were taken since the difference in the stem areas between apples was larger than that of the calyx areas.

Apple images with dimensions of 416 × 416 were captured, which included various postures, colors, textures, and some of them with different defects. As shown in Table 1, all images were divided into four datasets: training set, validation set, testing set and detection set. The training set and validation set were used for model training, the testing set was used to test the performance of the algorithm, and the detection set were used to detect the generalizability of the model. For 3455 original images of Luochuan Fuji acquired by camera: training set contained 1208 images, while validation set and testing set were 691 images, respectively (the ratio of 3:1:1).

Training images with abundant information will improve the generalization performance of the model. At the same time, it could effectively avoid overfitting of the trained model. Considering that the different postures of apples were obtained by their rotation, this research used rotation and scaling method to enhance the original image for acquiring apple images with different postures and sizes. The original images were rotated clockwise and anticlockwise 5 times at 9 ° intervals, respectively. Then they were resized to 416 × 416. Finally, 5000 images generated by data augmentation were randomly chosen for model training (3730) and validation (1270) based on the computer hardware performance (the ratio of 3:1).

In summary, training set contained 5803 images, validation set were 1961 images, and testing set were 691 images. The remaining 4205 images were divided into detection set to evaluate the detection performance of models on different cultivars of apples.

Differing from detection set which just contains images, training set, validation set and testing set contained images and corresponding annotation files which need to be converted to PASCAL VOC formant (Everingham et al., 2010). Ground truth bounding boxes were drawn manually by LabelImg v1.8.1 (https://github.com/tzutalin/labelImg).

2.3. YOLO-v5

As one of the famous one-stage object detection algorithms, YOLO has been widely used because of its simple network structure and extremely fast detection speed since it was proposed. After several iterations, the problem of low detection accuracy and weak detection for small targets that existed in the past of YOLO series have been greatly improved.

The YOLO-v5 algorithm used in this study was mainly upgraded from YOLO-v3, adding mosaic, Focus, BottleneckCSP, SPP, PANet module (Jocher et al., 2020). As shown in Fig. 2A, YOLO-v5 was made of a backbone network, a detection neck and three detection heads. Firstly, training images were input to the network after mosaic processing. The backbone network was applied to extract image features at different scales. Connected to the backbone was the detection neck section, which played a role of feature fusion. 3 kinds of feature maps obtained by detection neck with scale from large to small would be used to predict small, medium and large targets respectively. Finally, these feature maps were divided into grids. For each grid, 3 prior boxes (anchors) would be used to predict the target boundaries. Prior boxes sizes were obtained by k-mean clustering the labeled dimensions of training images. Eventually, each detection box would output a feature vector, including predicted bounding box coordinate offset, object confidence and classification probability. If there were many prediction boxes that were generated for a single target, the best bounding box would be left by non-maximum suppression (NMS) to obtain the final detection result.

YOLO-v5 could be divided into YOLO-v5x, v5l, v5m and v5s from complex to simple, by setting different network depths and widths. Although better detection capabilities could be obtained by a more complex network, it also had a higher requirement for computer performance. In addition, its training and detection time would be longer. Therefore, it was necessary to find a suitable network for stem/calyx recognition that was in balance between detection performance and model complexity.

2.4. Hyperparameters evolution

Hyperparameters are parameters preset before formal training in deep learning. Appropriate hyperparameters could improve the performance of model. The YOLO-v5 algorithm contained 23 hyperparameters, which were mainly used to set the learning rate, loss function, and data enhancement parameters, etc. The default hyperparameters were trained from the COCO set. Since all the data in this study were very different from the public dataset, it was necessary to retrain the suitable hyperparameters.

YOLO-v5 could perform hyperparameter optimization by genetic algorithm, which mainly used the way of mutation to generate offspring based on the optimal combination of all predecessors with a probability of 0.9 and standard deviation of 0.2. At the same time, set a mutation interval to prevent hyperparameters from mutation to unreasonable ranges. In this study, 320 generations of iterative training were set, and the F1 and mAP of the model were used to evaluate and determine the best hyperparameters. In this research, a fitness function was defined as a weighted combination of F1 and mAP: F1 contributed 90 % and mAP contributed the remaining 10 %. The maximum fitness function value in the evolutionary process means that the corresponding hyperparameters are optimal.

2.5. Transfer learning

As a popular method in the field of deep learning, transfer learning could improve the efficiency and robustness of model training. Usually, shallow convolutional networks are mainly used to extract generic features and focus on individual recognition, such as color, shape, edges, etc. While deeper networks place extra emphasis on learning task-specific features, mainly for target classification (Koirala et al., 2019a). Based on the characteristics of transfer learning, the detection algorithm used the pre-trained weight during training, which would not require random initialization. This training method could reduce the search range of the model and improve the training efficiency.

The YOLO-v5 algorithm could use the pre-trained weight trained from the COCO dataset, which contained 1.2 million targets in 80 categories (Lin et al., 2014). Although the pre-training weight contained a wealth of general features, the COCO dataset was very different from the recognition target of this study. Therefore, it was necessary to determine whether transfer learning was effective in detecting stem/calyx by F1 and mAP of the model.

2.6. Algorithmic optimization

In contrast to laboratory conditions, practical agricultural production often has to face some limitations in hardware conditions. Only deep learning algorithms that are simple and efficient enough are likely to be widely used. These networks usually take up less memory space and use a smaller number of parameters, while they can still perform similarly to larger models.

Although the general YOLO-v5s algorithm could perform the stem/calyx detection task well, the network could only reach 19.25 FPS with CPU (Table 4). Considering the performance of the equipment used in actual agricultural production is not as powerful as that of the server, it is necessary to optimize the algorithm structure for the training dataset to reduce the complexity of the algorithm and improve the detection efficiency.

The algorithm optimization process was shown in Fig. 3. First, the detection model was trained normally to obtain the initial weight. Then, a reasonable sparse rate was chosen for sparse training to obtain the sparse weight, which was the basis for subsequent optimization. The optimization process could be divided into detection head searching, layer pruning and channel pruning. It was also necessary to fine-tune the network based on the pruned weight to recover the performance loss caused by network adjustment. In the process of detection head searching, layer pruning and channel pruning, the detection performance (F1 and mAP), model complexity (layers, parameters and volume) and detection speed (FPS) of the models under corresponding settings should be compared to determine the optimal setting for the balance of detection efficiency and effectiveness, then the optimal stem/calyx detection network was acquired.

  • •

    Detection head searching

In order to optimize the algorithm, the number and size of detection heads are selected in the first. The original YOLO algorithm had three detection heads, with dimensions of 52 × 52, 26 × 26, 13 × 13. On this basis, 104 × 104 had been added. According to the order of the number and size of detection heads from large to small, 8 kinds of network structures were set, and anchors were also reset according to the corresponding network. Details could be found in the supplement. Every network structure was retrained, and then the detection performance and complexity of the model were compared, the best number and size of detection heads were selected, which were suitable for stem/calyx detection.

  • •

    Layer pruning

The shortcut layer was generally used to solve the problem of gradient divergence in deep networks. Layer pruning was based on the scaling factor (γ) mean value of the Conv layer before each shortcut layer in the BottleneckCSP module of backbone. By setting the number of layers to be pruned, the γ-means of each layer would be sorted and the corresponding layer was pruned from smallest to largest. To ensure the structural integrity of the module, the corresponding BottleneckCSP layers would be pruned together. Therefore, the maximum number of layers pruned should not exceed the number of BottleneckCSP in the YOLO-v5s backbone. Finally, 7 values (from 1 to 7) were selected for layer pruning to retrain the model separately. The optimized network backbone structure would be determined.

  • •

    Channel pruning

The channel pruning method used in this paper was first proposed by (Liu et al., 2017). The importance of channels could be evaluated based on the scaling factor (γ) of the BatchNorm2d (BN) layer which was used in Conv model and BottleneckCSP model. A larger γ could be considered that the channel was important for the recognition model. And a channel with smaller γ would be pruned, conversely.

The channel pruning ratio parameter was set to determine the pruning threshold. By sorting γ after sparse training, the channels below the threshold in the γ sequence could be pruned. If the γ of all channels in the whole layer was below the threshold, at least one of them was retained according to γ value size, particularly. 9 channel pruning ratios were set from 0.1 to 0.9 (an interval of 0.1) in the study. The best channel pruning ratio would be obtained through the comparison of 9 retrained models.

2.7. Evaluation indexes of model performance

As shown in Eqs. (1–7), detailed evaluation parameters are defined as follows: The loss of YOLO-v5 was used to evaluate the degree of inconsistency between the model prediction results and the ground truths, and it consisted of three components: bounding box loss (lbbox), object loss (lobject) and classification loss (lclassification). In order to prevent underfitting or overfitting of the model, the loss of training set (training loss) and verification set (validation loss) would be observed in the process of training to obtain the best detection model. True positive (TP), false positive (FP), true negative (TN), and false negative (FN) are used to calculate precision (pre)and recall (rec). The weighted summed average of precision and recall could be used and denoted by F1-score (F1). Compared with F1, mean Average Precision (mAP) could reflect the global detection performance of the model. mAP is the mean value of each category (c) of AP, and AP could be obtained by calculating the area under the corresponding precision-recall curve. In this paper, frames per second (FPS) was also used to characterize the real-time detection performance of the algorithm. Generally, it is necessary to achieve 24 FPS to guarantee real-time detection. 2.8. Parameters setting and hardware

Based on the previous experimental results and hardware performance, the parameters used for network training, optimization, and performance detection were shown in Table 2. The experiments were carried out on a server with Ubuntu (18.04.4) and a computer with Windows 10. Model training and testing were implemented on the server with following specifications: Intel (R) Xeon (R) Gold 6147 M CPU @ 2.50 GHz, 252 GB RAM, NVIDIA TITAN RTX (24 GB VRAM). For model detection, a PC with following specifications was used: Intel (R) Core (TM) i7-9700KF CPU @ 3.60 GHz, NVIDIA RTX2080 GPU (8 GB VRAM) and 32 GB RAM. The code for experiments was written in Python 3.8.0 and Pytorch 1.6.0.

3. Results and discussion

3.1. Influence of hyperparameters and transfer learning

To determine the best way to train, the study compared training models using different hyperparameters and ways of training initialization. Two sets of hyperparameters used for training were compared, while one set of the default hyperparameters was obtained from the evolution of the COCO dataset training, the other set was obtained using the evolution of the dataset in this study. And two adopted ways of train initialization were random initialization and transfer learning.

The results of training with different hyperparameters and ways of train initialization were shown in Fig. 4. Using evolved hyperparameters could produce lower loss during training and validation. The precision and recall of the model were more balanced, and hence the F1-score were higher. Compared to random initialization, the loss of model converged faster and lower in training when using transfer learning.

And the results of testing were shown in Table 3. Different training settings could have a significant influence on model detection performance, with F1 increasing from 0.799 to 0.887. Under the same hyperparameters, using transfer learning would improve the F1 of the model by about 0.027 compared to random initialization. There was a huge difference between the two sets of hyperparameters. Whether transfer learning was used or not, using evolved hyperparameters could increase the model's F1 by about 0.061. Combining these two training settings, the detection precision of the model increased from 0.712 to 0.883 (24.02 %), and its recall did not lose much, only decreased by 3.57 %. By comparing the above experiments, a better detection performance could be achieved using transfer learning with evolved hyperparameters.

3.2. Definition width and depth of YOLO-v5 training network (baseline)

The training results of YOLO-v5 with different depths and widths were shown in Fig. 5. It could be clearly found that the more complex the network structure model, the lower the training loss convergence, but the higher the validation loss which means the more severe the overfitting of the model. While there was only a small improvement in the detection performance of the model.

The complexity of the model could be characterized by weight volume and the number of parameters. The more complex model, the higher these indexes are, and the more GPU memory it takes up during training. The detection performance and complexity of various models were detailed in Table 4. YOLO-v5x had the best detection performance, with F1 of 0.889, but its model was also the most complex with a model weight of 169.26 MB, 88453800 parameters. YOLO-v5s had the most simplified network architecture with a model weight of 14.08 MB, 7263180 parameters. YOLO-v5s had a simplified 91.68 % network structure with only 1.8 % loss of detection performance, and could detect video tasks up to 111.21 FPS with GPU, which was 77.78 % faster than YOLO-v5 × . By comparing the above experiments, it could be found that YOLO-v5s is more suitable for stem/calyx detection.

3.3. Algorithmic optimization results

After the optimization of model, the final network structure was shown in Fig. 2B. The detection performance of the model was shown in Fig. 6. It could be found that the optimized convolutional network decrease from the initial 191 layers to 118 layers, and the weight of the model decreased by about 71 % in terms of both parameters and volume. Because of the simplification of the network structure, the algorithm also showed a huge improvement in recognition speed. The detection speed was improved by 59.16 % with GPU. In particular, it could reach 25.51 FPS with CPU, which satisfied the requirement of real-time detection. With the compression of the model, there was a slight decrease in the detection performance. The mAP decreased by 1.57 % and F1 decreased by 2.52 %. It showed that after pruning optimization, the new network structure for this research was more reasonable and effective. According to the analysis of each recognition category, it could be found that the impact of algorithm optimization on the detection performance of each category was different, among which the biggest decline was the defect category. The mAP and F1 respectively decreased by 10.2 % and 5.8 %, while the recognition ability of apple, stem and calyx remained better, mAP and F1 were kept above 0.945 and 0.895 respectively. The optimized algorithm has a significant reduction in model complexity and hardware requirements, but the performance decline is limited. In particular, it could achieve real-time target detection with CPU after optimization. This greatly improves the possibility that the algorithm could be used in practical application scenarios such as embedded mobile terminals.

3.4. Comparison of different object detection algorithms based on deep learning

Object detection algorithms based on deep learning have been widely used in agricultural production since they were proposed. In order to obtain a real-time, accurate, reliable and implementation-friendly stem/calyx detection algorithm, different target detection algorithms were compared. However, there are often differences in computer hardware, parameter settings and data sets used in training and testing among previous studies, which could not be compared scientifically. In order to avoid the impact of these differences, this study retrained the commonly used target detection algorithms, such as Faster R-CNN (Ren et al., 2017), SSD (Liu et al., 2016), EfficientDet (Tan et al., 2020), YOLO, etc., and some YOLO-v5s backbone network were also replaced by smaller networks GhostNet (Han et al., 2020), MobileNet V3 (Howard et al., 2019), ShuffleNet V2 (Ma et al., 2018), respectively.

The testing results of these object detection algorithms were shown in Table 5. The comparison of testing results was mainly reflected in three aspects of detection performance, weight size and detection speed. It could be found that: The two-stage target detection algorithm Faster-RCNN has the best performance in detection performance, with its mAP and F1 being 0.926 and 0.921, respectively. YOLO-v5s has the best performance among the remaining one-stage algorithms, and its mAP and F1 are 0.894 and 0.873, respectively. After algorithm optimization, the model performance is slightly lower than that of YOLO-v3 with 0.882 mAP and 0.86 F1, but still higher than the remaining algorithms; Compared with the remaining target detection algorithms in terms of weight volume, the optimized YOLO-v5s algorithm is much smaller than the other conventional algorithms, only 4.07 MB, which is similar to the size of common mobile networks; Faster R-CNN is the slowest detection method, it is much lower than other one-stage target detection algorithms. The remaining one-stage algorithms except EfficientDet, all of them can achieve faster detection speed with GPU, but only YOLO-v5s (MobileNet v3) and optimized YOLO-v5s could achieve real-time detection with CPU. The study results show that the optimized YOLO-v5s could realize the best balance in detection efficiency and effectiveness, and could be selected as the best stem/calyx recognition algorithm by combining the three indicators.

3.5. Detection performance of the algorithm for different apple cultivars

Apples of different cultivars and different growing areas will reflect different appearance characteristics, such as color and texture. To verify the performance in detecting stem/calyx of different apples, six kinds of apples in the detection set were detected. The specific results are shown in Table 6. Overall, the detection accuracy of the algorithm reached 93.89 %, and the detection accuracy for stem/calyx was similar with 93.59 % and 94.32 %, respectively.

Table 6. Accuracy of stem/calyx detection with optimized yolov5s for different apple cultivars.

Typical detection cases could be found in the supplementary material. The algorithm showed good detection performance for most apples. Although only Luochuan apples were used in the training set, they already contain general apple features. The algorithm could still make effective recognition for other similar apples with the effect of data enhancement and mosaic. When the stem/calyx is at the edge of the field of view, it is more difficult to detect. And the algorithm will be more prone to missed targets or false detections, because its main features have been obscured by the concave structure. The tiny defective spots are not easily detected due to the limitation of the algorithm; the detection accuracy for Ruiyang apples is only 83.07 %, which is much smaller than the detection ability for other cultivars. The reason for this difference is that Ruixue has different appearance characteristics from other apples. Compared with other cultivars, Ruixue is closer to a sphere overall. The difference between the stem region and the calyx region is small, which makes it almost impossible to determine their category with the human eyes in some angles. Therefore, the algorithm has the weakest detection ability for them. In order to solve this problem, the most direct improvement method could add these special apple images to the training set to improve its generalizability.

Compared with the calyx region, the apple stem region varies greatly, especially the length of the fruit stem. But the experimental results show that all types of stems could be effectively identified by the algorithm. In contrast, the position of stem in the image is the biggest factor affecting algorithm recognition. However, the application scenario studied in this paper is not for static fruit stem/calyx recognition, but for real-time discrimination when the fruit is rotated on the posture adjustment device. And the influence of the position of the stem/calyx in the image will be minimized due to the continuous change of its own posture. Therefore, the algorithm used in this paper could be used in the real-time recognition task of fruit stem/calyx, and provide technical support for the real-time posture adjustment of apples.

4. Conclusion

In order to solve the requirements for posture recognition in the process of fruit commercialization, this research proposed an object detection algorithm based on YOLO-v5 that could achieve the real-time detection of apple stem/calyx. Based on the recognition objects, hyperparameters of algorithm were determined, and the training method of transfer learning was adopted to obtain better detection performance. The study compared the backbone of YOLO-v5 networks with different widths and depths, and the results showed that under the same setting conditions, YOLO-v5s had a superior usability considering detection performance, model weight size, and detection speed. By comparing the number of detection heads and feature map sizes, layer pruning, and channel pruning for optimization of YOLO-v5s, the complexity of the algorithm was further reduced, and the model parameters and weight volume were decreased by about 71 %, while mAP and F1 were only decreased by 1.57 % and 2.52 %, respectively. After optimization, the algorithm could achieve real-time detection under CPU condition at a speed of 25.51 FPS. The detection performance of different object detection algorithms was compared. The method used in this study could obtain the best balance between detection performance and detection speed, which was friendly to hardware requirements making it had better practicality. The optimized YOLO-v5s achieved 93.89 % accuracy in fruit stem/calyx detection for different cultivars of apples.

The route of research techniques adopted in this paper will be equally applicable to other tasks that have special requirements for fruit posture. It could provide technical support to improve the level of commercialized automatic processing of fruit. The research that could be done in the future should focus on the detection and identification of defects, and the image acquisition system could be further improved to reduce their detection difficulty by using special spectral imaging techniques. In addition, apple images with special characteristics should be added to the training set to improve the generalizability of the algorithm.
